Thinly slice the @chestnut mushrooms{1}. Remove the top and bottom from the @courgette{1}, halve lengthways and chop into 1cm cubes. Grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pick the @sage{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Put a glug of @olive oil{2%tbsp} in a large #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Once hot, add the @gnocchi{1%packet} to the pan and fry until golden brown and crispy, ~{8-10%minutes}. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Meanwhile, combine the @panko breadcrumbs{30%g}, the @olive oil{2%tsp} and the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} for the crumb in a #small bowl{}, then set aside. Zest and halve the @lemon{1}.

Add the mushrooms to your (now empty) frying pan and return it to medium-high heat. Add a glug of @olive oil if the pan is dry. Cook, stirring occasionally, until golden brown, about ~{5%minutes}. Next, add the courgette and cook for ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the sage and garlic and cook until fragrant, another ~{1-2%minutes}.

Preheat your #grill{} to high. Return the gnocchi to the pan and remove it from the heat. Add the @crème fraîche{1%tbsp}, a pinch of lemon zest and the @water{100%ml}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}, add a squeeze of lemon juice and stir to combine.

Transfer the gnocchi and sauce to an #ovenproof dish{}. Sprinkle over the crumb mixture and finish with a good grind of black pepper. Grill until golden brown on top, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Put the @wild rocket{1%bag} in a large #bowl{}. Drizzle over the @olive oil{1%tbsp}(for the dressing), add a squeeze of lemon juice, season with salt and pepper and toss well.

> Pan-frying gnocchi brings a whole extra dimension to these pillowy little dumplings. The golden, crispy exterior provides a beautiful contrast with creamy sauce.

> This recipe serves 2 and takes about 30 minutes.

> The nutrition per serving is approximately 713 kcal, 22 g fat, 14 g saturated fat, 100 g carbohydrates, 8 g sugar, 27 g protein, 4 g sodium, with a serving size of 658.